---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-brazil', text: 'Leaving Brazilian Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'portuguese-support', text: 'Portuguese Language Support', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Portuguese Expat Insurance', href: '/best/portuguese-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'portugueseSupport', header: 'Portuguese Support' },
  { key: 'usNetwork', header: 'US Network' },
  { key: 'brazilCoverage', header: 'Brazil Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', portugueseSupport: 'Yes', usNetwork: 'Strong', brazilCoverage: 'Add-on (expensive)', price: 'R$950/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', portugueseSupport: 'Yes', usNetwork: 'Excellent', brazilCoverage: 'Add-on (expensive)', price: 'R$1,100/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', portugueseSupport: 'Limited', usNetwork: 'Good', brazilCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'R$900/mo' },
  { provider: 'SulAmérica', portugueseSupport: 'Full', usNetwork: 'Limited', brazilCoverage: 'Included', price: 'R$700/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bradesco Saúde', portugueseSupport: 'Full', usNetwork: 'Limited', brazilCoverage: 'Included', price: 'R$650/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Brazilian Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Brazilian expats. Find coverage for the US, Portugal, Japan, and other destinations with Portuguese language support."
  headline="Best Insurance for Brazilian Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Brazilians are one of the largest expat communities worldwide. Here's how to stay covered in the US, Portugal, Japan, and beyond—with Portuguese support when you need it."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/brazilian-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Brazilian expats are found worldwide—in the US (especially Florida and Massachusetts), Portugal, Japan, UK, and across Europe. Understanding healthcare options and finding Portuguese-speaking support matters. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Brazilian expats. Strong US networks, Portuguese support available.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent worldwide networks. Portuguese support through Bupa.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices.</li>
    <li><strong>SulAmérica:</strong> Major Brazilian insurer with international products. Full Portuguese support, Brazil included.</li>
    <li><strong>Bradesco Saúde:</strong> Brazilian insurer with some international coverage. Familiar service.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Brazil Coverage Warning"
    description="Brazilian healthcare is expensive in the private sector. International policies including Brazil as a covered region carry premium pricing. Consider whether you need Brazil coverage or can manage visits differently."
    buttonText="Compare Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-brazil">Leaving Brazilian Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Brazil has both public and private healthcare. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>SUS (Sistema Único de Saúde)</h3>
  <p>
    Brazil's public healthcare system (SUS) is available to all in Brazil—including visitors. It's free but often overcrowded with long waits. SUS doesn't extend abroad—it's Brazil-only coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Brazilian Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Private health insurance (planos de saúde) from Brazilian companies provides domestic coverage. Most don't extend internationally. Some offer limited emergency coverage abroad.
  </p>

  <h3>International Coverage from Brazilian Insurers</h3>
  <p>
    Major Brazilian insurers (SulAmérica, Bradesco Saúde, Amil) offer international products. Networks abroad are typically limited compared to global specialists, but Portuguese service is excellent.
  </p>

  <h3>Currency Considerations</h3>
  <p>
    Brazilian Real (BRL) volatility affects insurance costs. USD or EUR-denominated policies protect against currency fluctuation. Consider currency denomination when choosing coverage.
  </p>

  <h2 id="portuguese-support">Portuguese Language Support</h2>
  <p>
    Native Portuguese support matters during medical emergencies:
  </p>

  <h3>Brazilian Insurers</h3>
  <p>
    SulAmérica and Bradesco Saúde offer full Portuguese service—familiar terms, Brazilian Portuguese understanding. This can reduce stress during medical situations.
  </p>

  <h3>International Insurers</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna and Bupa have Portuguese support through their Latin American operations. Quality varies—Portuguese from Portugal is available through Cigna's European operations.
  </p>

  <h3>Local Support in Key Destinations</h3>
  <p>
    In areas with large Brazilian communities (Miami, Newark, Lisbon), Portuguese-speaking healthcare providers are available. Your insurance covers any qualified provider.
  </p>

  <h3>Claims and Documentation</h3>
  <p>
    International insurers accept documentation in multiple languages. Portuguese documents are typically accepted, though translation may expedite processing.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Portugal Opportunity</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Portuguese citizenship through ancestry is available to many Brazilians. This provides EU healthcare access. Consider this pathway when planning long-term European residence.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage with strong US networks—important for the large Brazilian community in Florida and Massachusetts. Portuguese support available. Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    Brazil coverage can be added but is expensive due to private healthcare costs. Good option for established expats.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Brazilian expats wanting reliable US coverage with Portuguese support.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent worldwide networks. Portuguese support available. Top-tier service quality.
  </p>

  <p>
    Brazil coverage available at premium cost. Higher pricing reflects premium positioning.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Brazilian professionals who want top-tier coverage and service.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong networks in Europe—valuable for Brazilians in Portugal and other EU countries. Good value option.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Brazilian expats in Europe seeking good value with strong EU networks.
  </p>

  <h3>SulAmérica</h3>
  <p>
    SulAmérica is one of Brazil's largest insurers and offers international products. Full Portuguese service, familiar processes, Brazil coverage included automatically. International networks are more limited than global specialists.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Brazilian expats who prefer familiar service with seamless Brazil coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Bradesco Saúde</h3>
  <p>
    Bradesco Saúde offers some international coverage options. Full Portuguese service from a familiar Brazilian brand. Brazil coverage included. International networks are limited.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Brazilian expats who want familiar service and prioritize Brazil coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Portuguese-Support Options"
    description="Portuguese language support matters during emergencies. Compare options that offer the service level you need."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Brazilian diaspora is found in specific concentrations:
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    Largest Brazilian diaspora—concentrated in Florida (especially South Florida), Massachusetts (especially around Boston), and New York. US healthcare is expensive—comprehensive coverage essential. Many Brazilian communities have Portuguese-speaking providers.
  </p>

  <h3>Portugal</h3>
  <p>
    Increasingly popular due to language and citizenship pathways. Portuguese SNS (national health service) covers legal residents. Private insurance supplements public coverage for faster access.
  </p>

  <h3>Japan</h3>
  <p>
    Large Brazilian community, particularly those of Japanese descent. Japanese health insurance covers employed workers. International insurance covers those outside the Japanese system.
  </p>

  <h3>United Kingdom</h3>
  <p>
    Growing Brazilian community in London. NHS covers legal residents. Private insurance supplements NHS for faster access.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does SUS cover me abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. SUS only provides healthcare in Brazil. You need separate international insurance for coverage abroad. SUS does cover you when visiting Brazil.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Brazil coverage expensive?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes. Private healthcare in Brazil is expensive. International policies including Brazil carry premium pricing. Consider whether you need this or can use SUS during visits.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about Portuguese citizenship?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Many Brazilians qualify for Portuguese citizenship. This provides EU healthcare access. Worth exploring for long-term European residence plans.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Portuguese support important?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">It helps during stressful medical situations. Brazilian insurers offer full Portuguese service. International insurers have varying Portuguese capability.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is SulAmérica or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">SulAmérica offers Portuguese familiarity and includes Brazil. Cigna has stronger global networks. Choose based on destination priorities and service preferences.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about currency denomination?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">BRL policies are subject to currency fluctuation. USD or EUR-denominated policies provide stability. Consider this when comparing prices.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Brazilian expats need comprehensive international insurance—SUS doesn't cover you abroad. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> offers strong US networks with Portuguese support. <strong>Bupa Global</strong> provides premium worldwide coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>SulAmérica</strong> suits those who prefer familiar Brazilian service with included home coverage. <strong>Allianz Care</strong> offers good value for European destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider whether you need private Brazil coverage (expensive) or can use SUS for visits. Explore Portuguese citizenship for long-term EU healthcare access.
  </p>

</PageShell>
